description.narrative:
- Number of complaints, investigations, prosecutions and adjudications handled, dis-aggregated by type, gender and location;
- Change in the percentage of pre-trial detention rates across the country;
- Number of SGBV Crimes investigated, prosecuted and adjudicated;
- Number of judges, prosecutors, and public defenders trained, dis-aggregated by age, gender, educational attainment and location;
- Number of CSOs/CBOs legal aid providers under the project, disaggregated by location and type of services;
- Number of legal aid beneficiaries of the project, dis-aggregated by gender, age and location;
- Number of gender responsive national legal aid policy adopted;
- Number of legal aid providers with capacity to provide specialized legal aid services for women;
- Number of female pre-trial detainees with access to legal aid and assistance in all prison facilities in Liberia;
- Number of security ‘hot-spots and intra-community tensions/disputes reduced;
- Number of community policing action plans jointly developed between local police officers and community members;
- Number of security councils established and operational at both county and district level;
- Number of women from peace hots, peace committees and early warning structures that engage in community watch forums;
- Number of cases referred to the police through community policing structures at the local level

comment.narrative:
- Low capacities of justice and security institutions and personnel
- No proper plea-bargaining system in place; 
- 64% pre-trial detention rates (2017)
- 40 female pre-trial detainees have access to legal aid and assistance
- 52 SGBV crimes adjudicated and disposed of (2017)
- 300 judges, 75 prosecutors and 30 public defenders trained and deployed
- Low number of CSOs/CBOs providing legal aid and assistance; 
- Lack of a national gender responsive legal aid policy;
- 10% community legal literacy rate per county (2015);
- Limited presence, reach and coverage of community police and community watch forum officers;
- 4 county/district security councils established and operational;
- Limited number of women in peace-hots, community peace committees, and early warning structures;
-Limited cases referred to police through community peace committees/hots and early warning structures

- 54% pre-trial detention rates;
-100 SGBV crimes investigated, adjudicated and disposed of;
-350 judges, 75 prosecutors and 35 public defenders trained
-12 CSOs/CBOs empowered to provide legal aid and assistance; 
-20% increase in community legal literacy rate per county;
-200 legal aid beneficiaries;
-56 female pre-trial detainees assessed legal aid services
-A network of national legal aid framework and system set up

- In an effort to reduce overcrowding in prison facilities and pre-trial detention rate, 12 CSOs were empowered to provide legal aid services to ordinary citizens. This resulted in 573 pre-trial detainees (232 women); 163 children (61girls) in conflict with the law benefiting from the free legal services;
- The project strengthened the investigation and prosecutorial capacity of the SGBV Crimes Unit at the Ministry of Justice through the recruitment and deployment of 10 staff (2 prosecutors, 4 city solicitors, 2 case liaisons and 2 victim support officers) in Lofa, Nimba, Bong and Montserrado counties. In addition, the project supported the training of 280 specialized police officers (100 females) and 25 prosecutors (10 females) from 10 counties in criminal investigation and case file handling techniques. As a result, out of 534 cases received, 188 cases were tried and 172 convictions secured;
- Working closely with its civil society partners, police and the prosecutors the project supported the prosecution of 320 SGBV cases through the provision of free legal aid and representation leading to 13 convictions;
- Legal literacy and knowledge in local communities were increased through 40 awareness events and dialogues that fostered accountability and enabled public participation in governance; and
-The project supported the development of the National Legal Aid Policy and supported the recruitment and deployment of six additional public defenders to increase access to justice services and leverage the involvement of women led structures in community policing and community watch forum activities at local community level.
